{"abstract": "The case of Deeb Salem, a former Goldman Sachs trader, highlights an arbitration system that is weighted toward the big Wall Street firms, William D. Cohan writes in the Street Scene column.", "web_url": "https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/09/big-short-case-raises-questions-about-finra-arbitration/", "snippet": "The case of Deeb Salem, a former Goldman Sachs trader, highlights an arbitration system that is weighted toward the big Wall Street firms, William D. Cohan writes in the Street Scene column.", "lead_paragraph": "Deeb Salem, the former Goldman Sachs trader who helped devise the firm\u2019s brilliant and highly profitable proprietary bet against the mortgage market, has never been shy about trumpeting his accomplishments. Mr. Salem no longer works at Goldman \u2014 he decamped to GoldenTree Asset Management, a New York hedge fund, in 2012 \u2014 but his continuing lawsuit, which contends the firm shortchanged him about $21 million in bonus and deferred compensation during the years after the financial crisis, raises fresh questions about the fairness of Wall Street\u2019s compensation practices, its willingness to make scapegoats out of former employees and the arbitration system \u2014 run by the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority \u2014 that everyone who deals with Wall Street is forced to use to resolve {"abstract": "The International Monetary Fund has a few ideas about reforming the Wall Street incentives that played a leading role in the 2008 financial crisis and still pose a threat, William D. Cohan writes in the Street Scene column.", "web_url": "https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/09/i-m-f-takes-aim-at-wall-streets-pay-system/", "snippet": "The International Monetary Fund has a few ideas about reforming the Wall Street incentives that played a leading role in the 2008 financial crisis and still pose a threat, William D. Cohan writes in the Street Scene column.", "lead_paragraph": "We don\u2019t like to concede that a primary cause of the financial crisis was a Wall Street compensation system that rewarded executives, bankers and traders for taking big risks with other people\u2019s money without holding them the least bit accountable. And because we don\u2019t like to discuss such things in polite company, it is certainly unsurprising that six years later, not a single fundamental aspect of how Wall Street pays its top people has changed. The incentive system that handed out millions of dollars in bonuses to bankers and traders who packaged shoddy mortgages into securities and sold them as AAA-rated investments remains intact and no doubt is well on its way to planting the seeds for the next Wall Street-inspired financial crisis.", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [{"rank": 0, "subtype": "xlarge", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/10/08/business/dealbook/dbpix-scene/dbpix-wall-articleLarge.jpg", "height": 381, "width": 600, "subType": "xlarge", "crop_name": "articleLarge", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2014/10/08/business/dealbook/dbpix-scene/dbpix-wall-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": 600, "xlargeheight": 381}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "jumbo", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/10/08/business/dealbook/dbpix-scene/dbpix-wall-jumbo.jpg", "height": 651, "width": 1024, "subType": "jumbo", "crop_name": "jumbo", "legacy": {}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "superJumbo", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/10/08/business/dealbook/dbpix-scene/dbpix-wall-superJumbo.jpg", "height": 1302, "width": 2048, "subType": "superJumbo", "crop_name": "superJumbo", "legacy": {}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "thumbnail", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/10/08/business/dealbook/dbpix-scene/dbpix-wall-thumbStandard.jpg", "height": 75, "width": 75, "subType": "thumbnail", "crop_name": "thumbStandard", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2014/10/08/business/dealbook/dbpix-scene/dbpix-wall-thumbStandard.jpg", "thumbnailwidth": 75, "thumbnailheight": 75}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "thumbLarge", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/10/08/business/dealbook/dbpix-scene/dbpix-wall-thumbLarge.jpg", "height": 150, "width": 150, "subType": "thumbLarge", "crop_name": "thumbLarge", "legacy": {}}], "headline": {"main": "I.M.F. {"abstract": "In order to be of use, assistants like Cortana and Siri need to know a lot about you. Reading the companies\u2019 privacy statements can give you an idea of how much.", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/28/technology/personaltech/protecting-personal-information-from-virtual-assistants.html", "snippet": "In order to be of use, assistants like Cortana and Siri need to know a lot about you.
